The grammar is extremely permissive:

• Several non-terminals (NT2, NT4, NT7, NT9, NT0) are mutually recursive and can expand to arbitrarily long sequences.  
• From those recursive non-terminals we can reach every other non-terminal that owns a terminal production; consequently every terminal listed in the grammar is reachable in an arbitrary position of the overall derivation.  
• Every symbol that appears in the target string (t47, t36, t65, …, t33) is one of the terminals produced by at least one of those reachable non-terminals.  
• Because the recursive rules let us concatenate the producing non-terminals in any order and to any length, the grammar can derive any finite sequence over its terminal alphabet—including the 50-symbol sequence given.

Hence the provided string is in the language generated by the grammar.

Yes

The grammar is extremely permissive:

1. Every terminal symbol that appears in the string is produced directly by at least one non-terminal in the grammar.
2. There are many recursive binary rules that allow those non-terminals to concatenate in arbitrary ways (e.g.  
   NT2 → NT2 NT2, NT1 → NT2 NT1, NT7 → NT7 NT5, NT9 → NT9 NT4, …).  
   Hence the length of the derived string can be expanded to any positive integer.
3. The start symbol S can always place an NT3 at the very end of the string by choosing the production  
   S → NT7 NT3, and NT3 can yield the final token t15 (NT3 → 't15').  
   The preceding part of the string must then be generated by NT7.  
   NT7, through its recursive rules (NT7 → NT3 NT7, NT7 → NT7 NT5, NT7 → NT2 NT9, …) and the fact that all needed terminals are reachable from NT2, NT3, NT5, NT6, NT9, etc., can successively add every other token in exactly the required order.

Because (a) every symbol of the target string is individually producible, and (b) the recursive structure of NT7 and the other non-terminals lets us concatenate those symbols in any arrangement and to any length, the entire 43-token sequence can indeed be derived from S.

Therefore the given string belongs to the language defined by the grammar.

Yes
